Courage (2019) 

In honor of Martin Luther King Day I wanted to share this photo and a quote from him: “An individual has not started living until he can rise above the narrow confines of his individualistic concerns to the broader concerns of all humanity.” 

And also a quote from a huge inspiration of mine, Maya Angelou, who said, “My mission in life is not merely to survive, but to thrive; and to do so with some passion, some compassion, some humor, and some style.”

🎨 𝕮𝖔𝖑𝖑𝖊𝖈𝖙𝖊𝖉 𝕸𝖚𝖘𝖊- 𝕸𝖆𝖗𝖈𝖍 8𝖙𝖍 🎨 @secondhome_la 

We are ecstatic to have Donna Isham exhibit her work at #CollectedMuse- There are two days left, so make sure to snag those tickets! 𝗧𝗶𝗰𝗸𝗲𝘁🔗 𝗶𝗻 𝗯𝗶𝗼- See you there, and thanks for the support! 💘

𝗗𝗼𝗻𝗻𝗮 𝗜𝘀𝗵𝗮𝗺 is an LA-based figuration and abstraction painter. She works intuitively across a variety of mediums including oil, cold wax, acrylic, charcoals, pastels, graphite, oil stick, ink, and pen. Isham’s paintings explore life and beauty in its many forms, sensuality and the ephemeral suggesting the spiritual and ecstatic. Her influence stems from her vast experience in the fashion, entertainment, and music industries. Her paintings are part of private and corporate collections, and her work has been exhibited at numerous galleries across the globe including New York City, Los Angeles, Miami, Aspen, Vienna, Paris, Nantucket, and in hotel lobby installations at the 𝗛𝘆𝗮𝘁𝘁 𝗛𝗼𝘁𝗲𝗹 and the 𝗦𝘁 𝗥𝗲𝗴𝗶𝘀 𝗦𝗻𝗼𝘄 𝗟𝗼𝗱𝗴𝗲. Her work has been exhibited during Art Basel in galleries 2018-2022 and was recently invited to exhibit at 𝗜𝗻𝘁𝗲𝗿𝘀𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗣𝗮𝗹𝗺 𝗦𝗽𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗴𝘀.

Isham’s career has also taken a philanthropic route, with Isham serving as the President of Artists for Human Rights Foundation, where she uses her creativity and expertise to create a more tolerant world. Most recently she was featured as an arts educator with nonprofit children’s organization, @theartofelysium, in Los Angeles.

Prism (2023)
58” x 67”

Acrylic, oil pastel on canvas 

Life is like a prism. You take the white light of light and it refracts or bends into all the colors of the spectrum.  And just like a prism the way you look through it depends on what light you see. I see life and what we can create, and the games that we can play and the effects that we can create as positive choices. Life,love, fun, and of course, challenges is what makes life worth living.

“Alchemy” - the title name of my exhibit at Art Basel this December ❄️

Alchemy is by definition the medieval forerunner of chemistry, based on the supposed transformation of matter. It was concerned particularly with attempts to convert base metals into gold or to find a universal elixir.  It is a seemingly magical process. That’s what painting is in its truest sense. It is creation and transformation of the blank canvas, the combination of raw elements of paint to find that magical elixir of artistic communication with emotional response. 

68” x 118”

Acrylic, graphite, oil stick, spray paint, ink on canvas
